{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"faaa4525-dc67-4085-8741-56074f885ad1","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe developer report confirms the root cause: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation overhead** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild in-process and uses a \"Fast Up-to-Date Check\" that skips MSBuild entirely when nothing changed.\n\nThe project itself is clean — no issues in the `.csproj`. The fix is in **how** builds are invoked.\n\n### Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop**\nKeeps the build host process warm and only rebuilds on file changes — closest to the VS experience:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n**2. Enable the MSBuild Server**\nReuses MSBuild worker nodes across separate CLI invocations, eliminating cold-start overhead:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build          # first build warms the server\ndotnet build          # subsequent builds reuse it\n```\n\n**3. Skip restore when packages haven't changed**\nNuGet restore check adds overhead on every build:\n```\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n**4. Ensure shared Roslyn compilation is active**\nThe Roslyn compiler server (`VBCSCompiler`) keeps the compiler warm between builds. It's on by default, but you can be explicit in the `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n```\n\n### Why VS is faster\n\nVisual Studio runs a **fast up-to-date check** entirely in-process before invoking MSBuild. If no inputs changed, it skips MSBuild altogether — cost is near zero. The CLI has no equivalent; it always launches MSBuild. Options 1 and 2 above close that gap.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bb02ca1a-5a84-42f7-b8f1-9885c0d84187","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified:\n- No analyzers slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets work correctly (targets skip)\n- The project compiles in <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server / keeps MSBuild in memory, avoiding the cold-start cost. The CLI `dotnet build` by default starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\n\nTo fix this, I should enable the MSBuild server which keeps the process alive between builds—either through the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable or the `-nodeReuse:true` flag. For development workflows, `dotnet watch` is another option that maintains a warm build process and only rebuilds when files change. `-nodeReuse:true` is typically enabled by default in `dotnet build`, though I should verify that `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` isn't set in the environment. For the dev workflow, `dotnet watch build` keeps the process warm and rebuilds incrementally on file changes. I could also try the `-graph` flag for better incremental builds, and there's a `<AccelerateBuilds` property worth exploring.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the key difference between Visual Studio and the CLI: VS has a \"Fast Up-to-Date Check\" that runs before MSBuild and skips the entire build if nothing changed, whereas the CLI always invokes MSBuild even for no-op builds, which adds startup overhead. So the practical recommendations are using `dotnet watch` to keep the process warm, enabling MSBuild Server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` to reuse nodes across invocations, and considering the `-tl` flag to reduce terminal output overhead.\n\nI can also add a project-level optimization by enabling shared compilation explicitly in the `.csproj` to keep the Roslyn compiler server warm between builds. For the most impactful improvement though, `dotnet watch build` is the clear winner for iterative development since it eliminates the startup cost entirely and keeps everything in memory.","outputTokens":1671,"requestId":"7C31:39DF49:AACD98:C3344F:6A02792E"},"id":"85261208-ba35-4898-94c7-7fa37ddd08b7","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:24.307Z","parentId":"df627cc7-f4ea-4cd0-b9f0-baada734bf01"}
